ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, a novel strategy for detection, adsorption, removal, and recovery Hg2+ using an integrated ‘all in one’ approach was presented (Fig. 1
                     ). A novel multifunctional ratiometric fluorescent CDs based on xylan (XMR-CDs) through amidation reaction was designed and synthesized, and then loaded them into porous wood (XMR-CDs-DW) structures for detection and adsorption of Hg2+ via electrostatic adsorption and chemical binding. Applied to water purification and photothermal conversion applications, the removal and resued of Hg2+ realized the high value-added utilization of hazardous waste. XMR-CDs exhibited a rapid response and low detection limit of 1.7 nM towards Hg2+. The adsorption experiments confirmed that XMR-CDs-DW exhibited good Hg2+ extraction capacity of over 291.4 mg g−1. In addition, the upcycled material (XMR-CDs-DW-Hg2+
                     ) obtained by vulcanization of the saturated adsorbent (XMR-CDs-DW-HgS) exhibited a rapid solar steam generation rate of about 3.3895 kg m-2h−1. Importanly, water purified by XMR-CDs-DW-HgS could also be utilized for real-time to cultivate plant and zebrafish, which proving the feasibility and potential of solar desalination–cultivation integrated system. This work reveals new possibilities for developing multifunctional biomass carbon dots for sustainable water purificated Hg2+. It is expected that this research will provide impetus for preparation of multifunctional materials suitable for detection, purification of heavy metal ions in polluted water, and capable of upcycling into value-added materials after saturation for environmental protection.

